	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Getting someone to do a let's play of your homebrew game</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Your game looks like one of the better ones currently in development, so I highly encourage you to keep on working hard <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />But... I've seen your message on Nintendo Age &amp; here and would like to suggest you few basic rules when you want to get feedback (either on in progress productions or also proper releases). Certainly this will take little longer than what you rushed out, but at the end it will raise more attention towards the people you want to attract.<br /><br />a) Screenshot! (if you do not have space, there are free picture hosters) -&gt; you are entirely missing them<br />b) Video! -&gt; Well, you did that, but you said on your own it was one month old. no one will be able to see the progress work of one month with an old video<br />c) Text/Description should be better repositioned and brought straight to the point. What is it? What is it about? What do you want? Always talk about yourself in the third person... there are so many &quot;I's&quot; you know... (at least in the very beginning!)<br />Something like: Hiatus War by srndwave is a Metroidvania type game with six bosses and about 50 levels. The game is about 40-50% done and I'd like to ask everyone here for some feedback. Download the game here... If you want to beta-test, please get in touch with me via ...&quot;<br /><br />other thoughts:<br />* considering you want to attract beta-testers, how should they get in touch with you if that person does not have a na or nesdev account?<br />* do not rely on &quot;let's play&quot; authors, as long as your game is yet not finished. they will feel like you want to waste their time. there is also no point in playing a game which is not yet fully developed. just imagine they will accept your request, you think you'll get a second chance once the game is done? everyone will see a lets play of your &quot;old garbage&quot; and the final product remains unrecognized.<br />* try to get the word out onto the various homebrew pages and retro-gaming pages, sure it's lots of work, but it will work out at the end. especially for such pages, it's important to have material to work with (screenshots/video).<br />* if your game is supposed to be that &quot;massive&quot; (I'd call 50 levels massive) it will for sure get attention, but people need to get a place for updates, consider a small blog for your game.<br /><br />hope this doesn't sound too rude, but there is so much potential behind your game - you should really put some energy into public relation / marketing too <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br />regards<br />kojote

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


